🔹 allowedHeaders: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization']
These are headers the client is allowed to send in non-simple requests.

Content-Type: required if you send JSON or form data

Authorization: required if you send tokens, like JWT

🔥 Without this, your frontend will get blocked even before your route handler runs.

exposedHeaders: ['Content-Length']
This tells the browser:

“You’re allowed to read this header from the response.”

Browsers hide certain headers by default — so if you wanna read them in JS (like .headers.get('Content-Length')), you gotta expose them.


credentials: true
This allows:

Cookies

Authorization headers

withCredentials: true requests

